Bump Mapping/Normal Mapping
- Invented by James Blinn in 1978
- Letâ€™s approximate all the surface normals that come out of an object
- Letâ€™s keep the smooth surface, but change the surface normals
- N * L (N dot L, cosine)
-
- Mathematically
- Pretend we have a S dimension one way, and a bump function f(s) that says how
high the surface is
- The surface normal points at 0 in the s direction, and at 0 in the f(s) direction. N =
[0, 1]
- It also points at T = [1, 0]
- Nâ€™ is fake, weâ€™re changing the surface normal
- Nâ€™ = N - fâ€™(s)*T
- fâ€™(s) is the slope
- We tilt the surface normal either forward or backwards to give us a fake N
- 1D picture
-
- 2D picture
- Thereâ€™s a u dimension, and a v dimension
- At a given position (u,v), what is the bump value there? How high is that
surface? (Itâ€™s the height)
- ğ‘ƒ and are tangents
