Photoshop: Under the Hood
â— History
â—‹ First Paint Program: SuperPaint (1973)
â—‹ By Richard Shoip at Xerox PARC
â—‹ Photoshop was created in 1988
â–  Authors: Thomas Knoll and ___
â— Paint Programs
â—‹ Represent images as grids of pixels
â—‹ Image has finite resolution (ex. 1280 x 1024)
â—‹ Often used for touching up photos
â— Popular Paint Programs
â—‹ Photoshop
â—‹ Gimp
â—‹ Corel Painter
â—‹ Procreate
â—‹ Art Rage
â—‹ Clip Studio Paint
â— Drawing PRograms
â—‹ Paint programs â‰  drawing programs
â—‹ Drawing program represents images as collection of strikes (curves)
â—‹ Strokes: arcs, bezier curves, etc.
â—‹ Often called â€œvector graphicsâ€
â—‹ Stroke parameters stored (ex. Circle center)
â—‹ Can zoom in (to a stroke-based image) without loss of quality
â–  Where we have all the parameters to a digit with a lot of mantissa
â—‹ Illustrator and inkscape are popular examples
â—‹ PowerPoint also includes drawing tools
â—‹ Paint vs. Draw
â–  Pixels v. parameterized circles
â— Filters and Convolution
â—‹ Filter changes image pixels in a specific way
â—‹ Filtering is often done with a convolution
â—‹ Convolution is weighted sum of nearby pixels
â—‹ Weights say how nearby colors are combined
â—‹ Examples: edge detection and blur
â–  Blur: convolve with Gaussian
â— Pixels and Layers
â—‹ Photoshop represents images as Layers
â—‹ Each layer contains grids of pixels
â—‹ Each pixel has color (r, g, b, alpha)
â—‹ Alpha specifies transparency/opacity
â—‹ Where one layer is transparent, see
â— Composition Equation
â—‹ Alpha = 0, totally transparent
â—‹ Alpha = 1, totally opaque
â—‹ Alpha = 0.5, half color from lower layer
â—‹ Layer arithmetic guided by simple equation
â—‹ Nearly identical to volume composition
â—‹ Calculated from per-pixel colors and alpha
â—‹ Final color = alpha * top_layer + (1-alpha)*next_layer
â— Special Layers
â—‹ Special layers are operators (not pixels)
â—‹ Used to adjust colors:
â–  Brightness
â–  Contrast
â–  blue/yellow balance
â–  Etc.
â— Painting
â—‹ Use painting metaphor to modify pixel values
â—‹ Brush tool to add â€œpaintâ€
â—‹ Brush stroke places colors onto a layer along usersâ€™ path
â— Painting
â—‹ Brush is actually a small images
â—‹ Brush can be hard-edges or soft
â—‹ Soft parts given by alpha values
â—‹ Bush doesnâ€™t have fixed color
â—‹ Brush color comes from color selector
â— Many Other Tools
â—‹ Too many tools to cover!
â—‹ Will concentrate on a feW:
â–  Selection
â–  Hole filling
â–  Image warping
â— Selection
â—‹ Can select a portion of a layer
â—‹ Operations of selected regions:
â–  cut/copy/paste
â–  Transform: scale, rotate, translate
â–  Filter: blur, sharpen, lighten, darken
â—‹ Selection tools:
â–  Lasso, polygonal lasso, magnetic lasso
â—‹ Most advanced methods are image-aware
â–  Pay attention to where you click, and the color of the pixel
â–  High contrast edges
â–  Sharp color changes
â—‹ Image-aware selection based on active contours (most of them)
â— Active Contours
â—‹ Paper by Kass, Wilton, Terzopoulos (1988)
â—‹ Paper has over 26,000 citations
â—‹ Contour is usually curve similar to Bezier (with more control points)
â—‹ Control point positions guided by:
â–  User dragging
â–  Maintaining smoothness (minimal bending)
â–  Attraction to image edges (image-aware)
â—‹ Balance these using energy formulation
â— Active Contours in Photoshop
â—‹ Used for selection
â—‹ Magnetic lasso tool
â—‹ Quick selection tool
â— Hole Filling
â—‹ Remove portions of photos
â–  People
â–  Blemishes
â–  Telephone pole
â–  Etc.
â—‹ Called image inpainting
â—‹ Several approaches used
â—‹ Copy pixels from other parts of image
â—‹ Two problems:
â–  We want to match intensity when pixels are copied (especially at borders)
â–  Decide which parts to copy from
â— Poisson Image Editing
â—‹ Match source and destination intensities
â—‹ Key idea:
â–  Match intensities at borders
â–  Maintain local pixel contrast inside borders
â–  Keep relative intensities (we can change absolutes, but keep relatives)
â—‹ Do this by solving Poisson equation
â—‹ By Perez, Gangnet, and Blake (2003)
â—‹ Photoshopâ€™s â€œpatch toolâ€
â— Poisson Image Editing
â—‹ Qsource and target regions need to match
â—‹ Source pixel contrasts give gradients (vectors)
â—‹ Target region gives boundary value constraints (scalar image intensities)
â—‹ Poisson equation matches both sets of constraints
â–  Laplacian = 0 on boundary
â–  Maintain intensity gradients inside region
â—‹
â—‹
â— Patch MAtch
â—‹ Deciding where to copy from to fill in a hole
â–  Human can choose
â–  Algorithm can choose
â—‹ Patch match is algorithm to pick good regions
â—‹ By Barnes, Shechtman, Finklestein, Goldman (2009)
â—‹ Use image patches to decide what is good part to copy from
â—‹ Image patch is a small region (ex. 9x9 pixels)
â—‹ Compare colors between 9x9 regions (sum-of-squared-differences)
â—‹ For hole-finning, look for good matches at edge of holes, work inward
â—‹ Uses random tests to speed up process
â— Image Warping
â—‹ Create image distortions (source â†’ target)
â—‹ Often described in two parts
â–  Corresponding source and target landmarks
â–  Region of influence around landmarks
â—‹ Several kinds of landmarks:
â–  Points with radius
â–  Line segments
â–  Triangles
â—‹ Influence decreases with distance to landmark
â—‹ Influence functions often Gaussian (ball curve)
â—‹ Shape of influence often called a radial scheme
â—‹ Many variations
â— New Tools: AI Techniques
â—‹ Deep neural network techniques on the rise
â—‹ Embedded in paint programs
â—‹ Neural nets can modify an image
â–  Artistic filters
â–  Content-aware hole filling (inpainting)
â—‹ Natural nets can create images from scratch
â–  User provides description (â€œpromptâ€)
â–  Network creates new image in seconds
â—‹ Final lecture will discuss this in detail
â— How do we know if an image is fake or real?
â—‹ At this point, there are some tools that can tell if an image is real or not
â—‹ Currently, you can tell real from fake images pretty well by closely looking at
them (humans)
â—‹ Techniques are terrible at creating hands currently
â— Summary
â—‹ Layers are grids of pixels with color and alpha
â—‹ Combining of layers is controlled by alpha
â—‹ Brushes are small images that modify a layer
â—‹ Smart selection done using active contours
â—‹ Hole filling by Poisson equation (to match intensity and maintaining contrast)
â—‹ Warping by moving landmarks
