â– 
â—‹ Diffusion Models
â–  Easy to add noise to an image
â–  Add enough noise, the original image is gone
â–  Noise: each pixel is given a random RGB value
â–  Can each NN to learn how to de-noise image (diffusion models)
â–  Training data:
â— Pairs of images, one slightly noisier than another
â— Tell network how noisy the images are (t-value)
â— Network predicts the less-noisy one
â–  Diffusion Models
â— Add noise (easy to do)
â— Remove noise using neural network
â–  Diffusion Network (U-Net)
â— Slight variation of the autoencoder
â— Output size shld be the same size at input
â—
â— Diffusion Models
â—‹ Train diffusion models on many images
â—‹ Will learn to make that kind of image
â—‹ Example: train on images of dogs
â—‹ Input is noise, output is a dog
â— Diffusion Models
â—‹ Can use text ot guide image generation
â—‹ Dall-E, etc.
â—‹ Training data: image and text description
â—‹ Encode text into vector (ex. Size 768)
â—‹ Control the â€œstrengthâ€ of convolution layers based on text vector
â—‹ control based on neural networks method called attention
â–  Can gather info form parts of images and parts of text
â— Text-guided Image Generation
â—‹ Two main inputs to diffusion model:
â–  Noise image (pixels with random RGB)
â–  Text prompt (description of image you want)
â—‹ Other controls:
â–  Random number seed for noise image
â–  Amount of â€œguidance: (CFG, default often 7.0)
â–  Number of de-noising steps (20-30 typical)
â— Dall-E 2 Results (Popular Diffusion Model)
â—‹ Salvador Dali and Wall-E
â— Stable Diffusion
â—‹ Generative diffusion model
â—‹ Network and code are free
â—‹ Many ways to run it:
â–  Pay site
â–  Run on your own machine (need good GPU)
â–  Google colab notebook (maybe not anymore)
â— Prompt Engineering (controlling Image)
â—‹ Small text changes can have big effect on images
â—‹ Not always obvious what text changes will do
â—‹ Users often experiment to find good prompts
â—‹ Can wander thru â€œprompt spaceâ€
â— Img2Img (controlling image)
â—‹ Can initialize with image
â— Inpainting (controlling image)
â—‹ Erase part of an image
â—‹ Ask system to â€œfill in: the missing piece
â—‹ Prompt guides what is added
â— Outpainting (controlling image)
â—‹ Adding to the outside of an image rather than from the inside
â—‹ Extend an image to make it larger
â—‹ Can extend at one edge, or all around image
â—‹ Guided by prompt, of course
â—‹ Can do this repeatedly to make huge images
â— ControlNet (controlling image)
â—‹ Uses guide image to control image generation
â—‹ Used together with prompt
â—‹ Guide image can be:
â–  Outlines of objects
â–  Depth image (similar to z-buffer)
â–  Skeleton of figure
